<span id="freeTextContainer1277671342306546857">This series has been on my TBR for what feels like forever.<br/><br/>Kate Burkholder is a protagonist I can get behind! Regardless of the fact that she seems somewhat invincible considering how teeny tiny she is. Painters Mill is town in Ohio with a large Amish population. Kate was a prior Amish lady herself before she was put under Bann. A serial killer from her past starts to murder again and Kate (as chief of police) sets out to solve this case and will her lifetime ago connection to this case get in t</span>
  <span id="freeText1277671342306546857" style="display:none">This series has been on my TBR for what feels like forever.<br /><br />Kate Burkholder is a protagonist I can get behind! Regardless of the fact that she seems somewhat invincible considering how teeny tiny she is. Painters Mill is town in Ohio with a large Amish population. Kate was a prior Amish lady herself before she was put under Bann. A serial killer from her past starts to murder again and Kate (as chief of police) sets out to solve this case and will her lifetime ago connection to this case get in the way?<br /><br />Parts of this early on were super descriptive and gory. There's one particular image of a copper electrical rod shoved into a dark crevice that I cannot stop thinking about. Castillo's writing kept the tension and made me flip through the pages to find out who was behind these murders. A few too many characters if you ask me, but I'm hoping they get fleshed out in future installations. I really enjoyed the down on his luck Tomasetti. I'm looking forward to the next book in this series.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1277671342306546857" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
